I am not advocating a great need for a new heal either (although less rarity on the 60 heal would be nice), in fact I put it a few steps below other needed priority spells.  What I am advocating is that chain-summoning does not automatically disqualify us from being able to heal our pets efficiently, like some people here seem to believe, just because we have a 'trick' we can do to replace a mostly dead pet with a fresh one.<br>
<br>
By that same logic a Beastlord should not have pet heals since they already have general purpose heals, and so pet heals are not 'needed'.<br>
<br>
What I am against here is the narrowmindedness.  I'm glad some mages enjoy chaining, great, do your thing.  It is a viable tactic....but it is not the gospel that mages MUST live by, and many prefer not to, instead believing in the way of the 'sustained pet'.  Saying those ones don't deserve a pet heal that can be at least partially as efficient as chaining is biased by thier own preference and has nothing to do with true balance.<br>
<br>
Raz says its a 'bad idea' to allow an efficient heal for pets.  Why? because he is ingrained to chaining.  I can just as easily say that its a 'bad idea' for a mage to be able to chaincast/reclaim pets for zero mana usage and be killing very powerful mobs while doing it, or regaining mana at unheard of rates by exploiting Reclaim.  Its all in the viewpoint, and we all have one.<br>
<br>
But...<br>
<br>
When someone like Raz, who takes it upon himself to be the 'voice' for mages is one of the people showing this bias, mages of the other persuasion feel like he isn't speaking for them...and they are right.<br>
<br>
Raz, if you really want to be that 'voice' you need to be more centered, and not toss away everything that doesn't fit into your picture with a &quot;You didn't prove it&quot; response.  If the 'voice' is too laden with your thumbprint then you are not speaking for all mages, but instead speaking your own opinion.<br>
<br>
See both sides.  <br>
<br>
With 2 weeks until PoP goes gold (CDs are burned) we don't have alot of time to build a consensus of what we need, and for the most part we are spinning our wheels on technicalities and minor issues.  Mages are the one spell casting class that has not had a single change(positive OR negative) to our initial spell line up yet (other then the typo on the 60 charm, and giving us access to the Imbues).  That is worrisome.  Either they are finalized, or they haven't received our feedback amongst the noise.<br>
<br>
Sage Finraziel <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 2047<br> <font color=#333333>(10/5/02 6:13:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm46.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=65.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: New Heal? How about the ones we have</span><hr size=1> Before I go off, it is entirely possible that the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Planes of Power</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> environment will require a pet heal upgrade, and that now is a critical time to ask for <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>that</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.  It is difficult to decide if one is needed without seeing the zones and mobs.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Finraziel:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  What I am advocating is that chain-summoning does not automatically disqualify us from being able to heal our pets efficiently<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Not quite what I am saying.  There are two different issues here.<br>
<br>
First, has to do with the question, is it <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>necessary</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->?  If there are other options, then an improved pet heal is not necessary.  If mages were prevented from doing something they reasonably ought to be able to do, and no other choice, then need would be clear.<br>
<br>
In this case, what the existance of chaining pets suggests that the magician in fact already has a choice: they can chain another pet instead of healing.  This weakens the necessity argument, because what you are saying is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &quot;I don't like this choice, give me another.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Arguing that you need something because you refuse to solve the problem using your existing capabilities does not make for a very convincing case.<br>
<br>
The second issue is one of balance and over powering.  Currently, chain casting is a viable alternative to sustaining pets, and has various tradeoffs.  Sustaining is faster, safer, but takes more mana.  Chaining take less mana, allows for somewhat stronger opponents, but is slower and much riskier.<br>
<br>
If heals were so good that you could almost always avoid chaining pets, then that would give the most of the benefits of chaining pets, with none of the risk.<br>
<br>
A limitation of the epic pet is that it is designed not to be chained well.  A heal that is a close substitute for chaining would be a strong upgrade to the epic pet, as chaining is a strong technique.  Does the epic pet need to be made stronger?  Probably not, or at least not in that way.<br>
<br>
The evidence is that the existing pet heals are adequate for the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Luclin</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> era.  While that may not be the case for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  PoP</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, all the concrete examples given in this and other threads using the existing pet heals has shown them to be adequate to the task at hand, i.e. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Yeldema, Ice Burrowers,</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> 4-arms, etc.<br>
<br>
The proponents of a super pet heal have yet to put forward as much as even one concrete example where the existing pet heals fail.  What mobs ought you to be able to solo that you can't because the existing pet heals are too weak?<br>
<br>
Instead mostly what I hear is that some mages want to play <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &quot;GI Joe&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> with their pets, and dress them up with all kinds of expensive gear.  Well you can do that now, and there is a cost versus reward of doing so: when the pet dies, you lose the gear.  Seems balanced to me.<br>
<br>
What are you saying then?  That the reward of giving them gear is outweighed by the costs?  Then maybe you should consider carefully under what circumstances you give more expensive gear to pets.  Like maybe in a group with a healer.<br>
<br>
You also seem to think that I am some kind of rabid chainer.  On the contrary, I chain or sustain as the situation dictates.  I have mules with big chunks of inventory devoted to pet weaponry, mostly gnoll hide lariats and yakeshas.  When do I bring it out?  When the reward is worth the cost.  Unless I am soloing low DPS opponents, I don't use whips.  When I am with a group with a real tank and healer, out come the whips, or, when I get my epic, the yakeshas.<br>
<br>
I already have the option to equip my pet, and the cost is already fair and balanced.<br>
<br>
I see the demands for a super pet heal as little more than a grab for raw power without any compensating cost or risk.  You want more power for less cost and less risk.<br>
<br>
I would rather ask for needed upgrades or fixes, like some solution for the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Wizard-Rod</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> problem, which <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>is</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> a gaping hole in the current class design for mages.  Which, incidentally, was made most clear to me by <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Finraziel</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
